art|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN696062</small>\n|Opinion has swung back and forth on whether this is a natural collection of stone slabs or a neolithic tomb. One explanation could be that the largest stones, the 'capstone' and a supporting slab, may be in situ, but were utilised to create a tomb, possibly covered by a cairn. The site is on a broad ridge of Mynydd Carnlechert, 60m west of the Carn Lechart burial (GM078), further down the slope, and can be seen from there.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.1</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[Neolithic British Isles|neolithic]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM480</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|93287}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00347w}}. Cadw SAM: GM480: Burial Chamber Nr Carn Llechart</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Carn Llechart - geograph.org.uk - 148935.jpg|80px|Carn Llechart cairn circle]]\n|Carn Llechart Stone Circle\n|[[Ring cairn]]\n|[[Pontardawe]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.74|-3.888|name=Carn Llechart Stone Circle|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN697062</small>\n|25 stone slabs, set on edge to form a circle 14 m across, on the skyline of a broad ridge of Mynydd Carnlechert. An open stone-lined cist 2.1 m long is in the centre. It was first noted in 1695 in [[William Camden]]'s ''Britannia''. It may once have had a mound, but it is more likely it was always a ring cairn, a raised ring with its central area at ground level. It is a burial site, thought to date to 1000-2000BC.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.3</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[Bronze Age Britain|Bronze Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM078</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301289}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00355w}}. Cadw SAM: GM078: Carn Llechart Stone Circle</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Mynydd y Garth Cairn\n|Round cairn\n|[[Pontardawe]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7529|-3.8701|name=Mynydd y Garth Cairn|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN710076</small>\n|Cairn of loose stones, on the ridge s