s on the upper Melin Court valley, also known as Caen Caca Marching camp. It is next to an Iron Age enclosure (GM366), very like the pairing of the enclosure and Roman camp at Blaen-Cwmbach, {{convert|3.7|km|mi}} to the west.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">2</span>[[File:blue pog.svg|10px]] [[Roman Britain|Roman]]<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM367</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|304777}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00875w}}. Cadw SAM: GM367: Roman Marching Camp South West of Melin Court Brook</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Coelbren Roman Fort\n|[[Castra|Roman fort]]\n|[[Onllwyn]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7835|-3.6548|name=Coelbren Roman Fort|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN859107</small>\n|[[Roman auxiliaries in Britain|Roman auxiliary]] fort at the northern extremity of Neath Port Talbot, next to the border with Powys. Construction began around 74 AD, with a second construction phase, possibly associated with the laying out of the [[Sarn Helen#Neath\u2013Brecon|Sarn Helen]] road, which heads NE from just outside the fort. Occupation ceased by the mid-2nd century. The fort was first documented in 1907.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">2</span>[[File:blue pog.svg|10px]] [[Roman Britain|Roman]]<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM146</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301348}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00526w}}. Cadw SAM: GM146: Coelbren Fort</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Coelbren Roman Marching Camp\n|[[Roman marching camp]]\n|[[Onllwyn]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7796|-3.6508|name=Coelbren Roman Marching Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN862102</small>\n|Large rectangular enclosure, {{convert|438|m|ft}} long, defining a Roman marching camp. It is less than 200 metres from Coelbren Roman Fort (GM146), on what is now rough wet land, bounded on three sides by the Camnant and Pyrddin rivers.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">2</span>[[File:blue pog.svg|10px]] [[Roman Britain|Roman]]<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM343</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301347}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00527w}}. Cadw SAM: GM343: Roman Marching Camp South East of Coelbren Fort</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|[[Hirfynydd]] fortlet\n|[[Castellum|Roman signal station]]\n|[[Seven Sisters, Neath Port Talbot|Seven Sisters]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7466|-3.6979|name=Hirfynydd Fortlet|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN828066</small>\n|A small square enclosure, 18\u00d719 metres, with rounded corners, high up on the {{convert|450|m|ft}} Hirfynydd ridge between the Neath and Swansea valleys. Situated on the Neath to Brecon [[Sarn Helen#Neath\u2013Brecon|Sarn Helen]] road, which it would have helped control, its other use is thought to have been as a signal station.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">2</span>[[File:blue pog.svg|10px]] [[Roman Britain|Roman]]<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM274</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|93165}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00541w}}. Cadw SAM: GM274: Hirfynydd Roman Earthwork</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Roman Camp Blaen Cwm Bach above Tonna, Neath Valley, Wales, Oct 2013.JPG|80px|Looking north along western side of the  Blaen Cwm Bach Roman marching camp]]\n|Blaen Cwm Bach Camp\n|Marching camp\n|[[Tonna, Neath|Tonna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6751|-3.7394|name=Blaen Cwm Bach Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS798988</small>\n|Rectangular Roman camp {{convert|880|m|yds}} from east to west, and {{convert|300|m|yds}} wide, defined by bank and ditch cut into the rocky ground, on the top of a broad ridge on the hill above Tonna. This is right next to an Iron Age enclosure (GM277), an arrangement repeated {{convert|3.7|km|mi}} at Melin Court camp.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">2</span>[[File:blue pog.svg|10px]] [[Roman Britain|Roman]]<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM258</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301344}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00616w}}. Cadw SAM: GM258: Blaen-Cwmbach Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Court Herbert Cross & Grave Slab\n|[[Celtic cross|Cross]]\n|[[Dyffryn Clydach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6633|-3.8219|name=Court Herbert Cross & Grave Slab|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS740976</small>\n|A pillar with two crosses carved into it (one 7th to 8th centuries, the other 9th century). A grave slab, reputedly of the first abbot of Neath Abbey, lies nearby. They are now close to the A4230 in Neath, possibly moved to what was then Court Herbert park in the 19th century.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">3</span>[[File:green pog.svg|10px]] Early Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM207</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301394}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00588w}}. Cadw SAM: GM207: Court Herbert Cross & Grave Slab</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Clawdd Mawr, Mynydd Caerau\n|[[Earthworks (archaeology)|Linear earthwork]]\n|[[Glyncorrwg]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.641|-3.5983|name=Clawdd Mawr, Mynydd Caerau|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS894947</small>\n|A bank and ditch running for 200m across a [[col]] separating Mynydd Caerau and the Mynyd Llangeinwyr ridge\n|<span style=\"display:none\">3</span>[[File:green pog.svg|10px]] Early Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM231</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307434}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02791.0w}}. Cadw SAM: GM231: Clawdd Mawr, Mynydd Caerau</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Stones Museum, Wales.JPG|80px|Margam Stones Museum, ground floor]]\n|Margam Inscribed & Sculptured Stones [[File:Cadw logo.png|20px|link=Cadw|Property in the care of Cadw]]<ref>[http://cadw.wales.gov.uk/daysout/margamstonesmuseum/?lang=en cadw.wales.gov.uk: Margam Stones Museum]</ref>\n|[[Celtic cross|Cross]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5637|-3.7312|name=Margam Inscribed & Sculptured Stones|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS801864</small>\n|A collection of carved stone pillars and crosses, mostly from the immediate locality, many dating to late Roman and early medieval periods, now housed in the [[Margam Stones Museum]], near [[Margam Abbey]]. The stones were collected by the Talbot family during the 18th and 19th centuries. Some of the stones have known source sites which are themselves scheduled. The museum is run by Cadw, and open to the public.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">3</span>[[File:green pog.svg|10px]] Early Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM011</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|94512}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|}}. Cadw SAM: GM011: Margam Inscribed & Sculptured Stones</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Sculptured Cross Llanmihangel Farm\n|[[Celtic cross|Cross]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.532|-3.7082|name=Sculptured Cross Llanmihangel Farm|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS816828</small>\n|Fragment of a Celtic 'cartwheel cross' head, now built into a wall east of Llanmihangel farmhouse. It may have originated from the nearby St Michael's Grange.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">3</span>[[File:green pog.svg|10px]] Early Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM345</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|19186}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00807w}}. Cadw SAM: GM345: Sculptured Cross Llanmihangel Farm</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Cefn Morfydd Dyke & Earthwork\n|[[Earthworks (archaeology)|Linear earthwork]]\n|[[Tonna, Neath|Tonna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.668|-3.7533|name=Cefn Morfydd Dyke & Earthwork|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS788980</small>\n|This bank with shallow ditch runs across the ridge of Cefn Morfydd, disrupted at its east end by an industrial tramway.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">3</span>[[File:green pog.svg|10px]] Early Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM264</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307208}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02790.0w}}. Cadw SAM: GM264: Cefn Morfydd Dyke & Earthwork</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Vicinity of Plas Baglan.JPG|80px|Plas Baglan fortified enclosure is probably amongst the trees beyond the clearing.]]\n|Plas Baglan\n|[[Castle]]\n|[[Baglan, Neath Port Talbot|Baglan]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6157|-3.7979|name=Plas Baglan|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS756922</small>\n|12th-century defensive house overlooking Baglan, occupied until the 17th century. Only a platform and traces of masonry remain.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM358</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307236}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00654w}}. Cadw SAM: GM358: Plas Baglan</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:St Baglan medieval Church, Port Talbot.JPG|80px|Ruined medieval church of St Baglan, Port Talbot]]\n|[[St Baglan's Church, Port Talbot|St Baglan's Church]]\n|[[Church (building)|Church]]\n|[[Baglan, Neath Port Talbot|Baglan]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6156|-3.8016|name=Ruins of St Baglan's Church|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS753922</small>\n|Medieval Church, now in the overgrown corner of the large churchyard. It appears to be a pre-Norman foundation, with two early Christian stones in the churchyard. It was replaced by a newer church in the same churchyard in 1882, but only became derelict after a fire in 1954.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM428</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|174}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00653w}}. Cadw SAM: GM428: Ruins of St Baglan's Church</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|St Margaret's Chapel\n|[[Church (building)|Church]]\n|[[Coedffranc]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6297|-3.8723|name=St Margaret's Chapel|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS705939</small>\n|First recorded in 1291, this was a chapel of St Margaret's Grange, an outlier of Neath Abbey. The site, near Jersey Marine, was excavated in 1931.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM362</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307238}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00642w}}. Cadw SAM: GM362: St Margaret's Chapel</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Hirfynydd house platforms. \n|House p