 pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM289</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307228}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00673w}}. Cadw SAM: GM289: Cwm-Clais Castle Mound</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Mynydd Drumau settlement platforms\n|House platform\n|[[Dyffryn Clydach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.687|-3.8417|name=House Platforms West of Dyffryn Wood|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN727002</small>\n|A group of house platforms, cut into the steep hillside below the summit of Mynydd Drumau.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM549</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|304630}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00812w}}. Cadw SAM: GM549: House Platforms West of Dyffryn Wood</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Neath Abbey and the Tennant Canal.JPG|80px|Neath Abbey and the Tennant Canal]] \n|[[Neath Abbey]] and Gatehouse [[File:Cadw logo.png|20px|link=Cadw|Property in the care of Cadw]]<ref>[http://cadw.wales.gov.uk/daysout/neathabbeyandgatehouse/?lang=en cadw.wales.gov.uk: Neath Abbey]</ref>\n|[[Abbey]]\n|[[Dyffryn Clydach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6612|-3.826|name=Neath Abbey & Gatehouse|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS738974</small>\n|Cistercian monastery, once the largest abbey in Wales. Following its dissolution, the Herbert Mansion was built on the Abbot's lodging, and the area then became an industrial site. The substantial ruins were excavated in 1924 and 1934, and taken into public ownership in 1944. It is now in the care of [[Cadw]] and open to the public. The 12th-century gatehouse is north of the New Road.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>(12th century)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM006</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|133}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00585w}}. Cadw SAM: GM006: Neath Abbey & Gatehouse</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Chapel above Margam Park - geograph.org.uk - 692289.jpg|80px|Hen Eglwys, a ruined chapel above Margam Park]]\n|Hen Eglwys\n|[[Chapel]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5648|-3.7308|name=Hen Eglwys|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS801865</small>\n|Also known as Cryke Chapel and dated to 1470, this grange of nearby Margam Abbey (GM005) is on the hillside of Craig-y-capel. The gable-ends, with window tracery are the principle survivals, and provided a gothic landmark and viewpoint for the 19th-century parkland of Margam Castle. There was a burial ground and a holy well known as Ffynnon Mair.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>(1470)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM163</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307267}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00765w}}. Cadw SAM: GM163: Hen Eglwys</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Castle and part of the old abbey - geograph.org.uk - 692191.jpg|80px|Margam Abbey with Margam Castle in the background]]\n|[[Margam Abbey]]\n|[[Abbey]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5623|-3.7298|name=Margam Abbey|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS801862</small>\n|Founded in 1147, St Mary's Abbey was dissolved in 1536. The nave survives as [[Margam]] parish church. The remainder of the abbey complex was acquired by the Mansel, and later the Talbot family, who incorporated the ruins into their parkland and [[Margam Castle]]. A 12-sided chapter house has been restored. The outer precincts may have occupied a much larger area than the currently defined inner core area.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>(1147)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM005</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|132}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00771w}}. Cadw SAM: GM005: Margam Abbey</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Margam Medieval Bath House\n|Bath-house\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5684|-3.7284|name=Margam Medieval Bath House|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS803869</small>\n|Also known as Ffynnon Fyggyr (medicinal well) this may be a healing well, though also used for baptisms by Hen Eglwys (GM163) and later as a Monastic baths for Margam Abbey (GM005). The present structure, 14th or 15th century but probably on an older site, has a stone vaulted roof over a 1m deep pool with original flagstones.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM545</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|32343}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|04796w}}. Cadw SAM: GM545: Margam Medieval Bath House</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Neath Castle - geograph.org.uk - 42391.jpg|80px|Neath Castle]]\n|[[Neath Castle]]\n|[[Castle]]\n|[[Neath]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6651|-3.8035|name=Neath Castle|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS753977</small>\n|Neath's second castle, this is first documented in 1183. (A castle of 1120 was located across the river near the Roman Fort - GM215) Destroyed in 1321 and rebuilt in 1377, this one was in use until the 17th century, and has been a recreational area for the town since the 18th century.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM039</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|94528}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00624w}}. Cadw SAM: GM039: Neath Castle</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:House Platforms - geograph.org.uk - 223804.jpg|80px|House Platforms on the north slope of Foel Fynyddau]]\n|Foel Fynyddau Deserted Rural Settlement\n|House platform\n|[[Pelenna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6351|-3.7595|name=Deserted Rural Settlement North of Foel Fynyddau|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS783943</small>\n|800m North of the summit of Foel Fynyddau two sets of earthwork house platforms and a sunken storehouse mark the location of a medieval settlement\n|<span style=\"display:none\">4</span>[[File:gold pog.svg|10px]] Medieval<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM551</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|15352}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00663w}}. Cadw SAM: GM551: Deserted Rural Settlement North of Foel Fynyddau</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Wenallt blast furnace, Blaengwrach.JPG|80px|The 'blowing house' of Venallt Blast Furnace]]\n|Remains of Venallt Ironworks\n|[[Ironworks]]\n|[[Blaengwrach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7319|-3.6459|name=Remains of Venallt Ironworks|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN864049</small>\n|Blast furnaces on the western edge of Cwmgwrach, built in 1839\u201342 to use anthracite-fired 'hot-blast' method of iron smelting. Also called Yr Wenallt.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM423</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34120}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01124w}}. Cadw SAM: GM423: Remains of Venallt Ironworks</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Tennant canal aqueduct over River Neath at Aberdulais.jpg|80px|Tennant Canal Aqueduct over the River Neath at Aberdulais]] \n|Aberdulais Aqueduct\n|[[Navigable aqueduct|Aqueduct]]\n|[[Blaenhonddan]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.679|-3.7762|name=Aberdulais Aqueduct|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS772992</small>\n|Built in 1823 to cross the River Neath and link the Tennant and Neath Canals. With 10 stone arches it is the longest aqueduct in South Wales.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM506</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34446}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02853w}}. Cadw SAM: GM506: Aberdulais Aqueduct</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Waterwheel, Aberdulais Falls - geograph.org.uk - 1367026.jpg|80px|Waterwheel and industrial remains, Aberdulais Falls]]\n|Tinplate works at [[Aberdulais Falls]] [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|<span style=\"background-color:green; color:white; border:1px solid #000000;\">&#160;NT&#160;</span>]]\n|Tinplate Works\n|[[Blaenhonddan]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6807|-3.7779|name=Tinplate works at Aberdulais Falls|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS771994</small>\n|Industrial site originating with waterpowered metalworking in 1584. Now open to the public\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM485</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|95689}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01085w}}. Cadw SAM: GM485: Tinplate works at Aberdulais Falls</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Incline Bridge - geograph.org.uk - 207119.jpg|80px|Bridge on the Ynysmaerdy Railway Incline]]\n|Ynysmaerdy Railway Incline\n|[[Railway]]\n|[[Briton Ferry]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6401|-3.8061|name=Ynysmaerdy Railway Incline|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS751950</small>\n|[[Cable railway|Inclined plane railway]], designed in the 1850s by Brunel to bring coal to Briton Ferry Docks, and abandoned in 1910\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1850s)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM489</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|412122}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02996.0w}}. Cadw SAM: GM489: Ynysmaerdy Railway Incline</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Waun y Coed Colliery Branch Canal and Tramroad Incline\n|Industrial monument\n|[[Cilybebyll]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7285|-3.8292|name=Waun y Coed Colliery Branch Canal and Tramroad Incline|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN737048</small>\n|Complex arrangement of tramway, canal branch, and canal dock, to link the Waun y Coed Colliery and nearby Ynyscedwyn Ironworks with the canal to Swansea. This required a tramway bridge over the River Tawe, now gone, and wharves and 300 m of canal, now filled in, that linked to the [[Swansea Canal]]. Several buildings and foundations of numerous structures remain.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1828)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM400</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34515}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01046.26w}}. Cadw SAM: GM400: Waun y Coed Colliery Branch Canal and Tramroad Incline</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|[[Neath and Tennant Canal|Tennant Canal]]: Skewen Cutting and tramroad bridge\n|[[Canal]]\n|[[Coedffranc]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6583|-3.8346|name=Tennant Canal: Skewen Cutting and tramroad bridge|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS731970</small>\n|A stone lined section of the Tennant Canal where it runs through the [[Skewen]] Cutting, in Neath. Built by William Kirkhouse in 1821, the canal linked the [[Neath Valley]] to [[Swansea docks]]. The stone lining was to counteract a problem with [[quicksand]]. The bridge carried a pre-existing horse-drawn railway, at a time when Britain was the only country in the world with surface railways.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1821)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM394</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34829}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01070.14w}}. Cadw SAM: GM394: Tennant Canal: Skewen Cutting and tramroad bridge</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Cwmafan copper works flue\n|[[Chimney]]\n|[[Cwmafan|Cwmavon]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6254|-3.7592|name=Cwmafan copper works flue|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS783933</small>\n|Culvert running up the hillside to a former stack on the summit of Foel Fynyddau. The flue vented fumes from copper smelting works, which were in use from 1838 to 1906. The stack was demolished in 1940 in case Luftwaffe bombers used it for navigation. Further damage occurred when a communication mast was built.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1838)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM566</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|401306}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|05784w}}. Cadw SAM: GM566: Cwmafan copper works flue</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Neath Abbey Ironworks blast furnaces - geograph.org.uk - 342093.jpg|80px|Neath Abbey Ironworks blast furnaces]]\n|Neath Abbey Ironworks\n|Industrial monument\n|[[Dyffryn Clydach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6644|-3.8268|name=Neath Abbey Ironworks|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS737977</small>\n|Two [[blast furnace]]s and engineering works, with a forge and rolling mill upstream. It was in use from the 1790s to 1885. They were acquired by the Fox and later Price families, who expanded to other sites in the Neath valley. Steam Engine manufacture was an early specialism and shipbuilding were amongst the items produced. Their Quaker principles meant they were against any production of armaments.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1790s)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM389</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|85096}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00854w}}. Cadw SAM: GM389: Neath Abbey Ironworks</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Machinery at Cwm Clydach pond - geograph.org.uk - 1358511.jpg|80px|Machinery at Cwm Clydach pond]]\n|Neath Abbey Ironworks Dam\n|[[Dam]]\n|[[Dyffryn Clydach]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6735|-3.8248|name=Neath Abbey Ironworks Dam|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS739987</small>\n|Dam on the river Clydach, to provide a constant water supply for the ironworks waterwheel. Built in 1840.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1840)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM395</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|33643}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01017w}}. Cadw SAM: GM395: Neath Abbey Ironworks Dam</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Ynys Fawr Corn-Drying Kiln\n|Corn-drying kiln\n|[[Glyncorrwg]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6403|-3.722|name=Cynon Corn-Drying Kiln|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS809948</small>\n|An inverted dry stone walled cone, set in the ground, provided a 3-metre-wide space over which skins could be stretched, and grain spread out. A connecting tunnel allowed a fire to warm the air under the grain, and dry it out ready for storage. \n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM546</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|33324}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|04787w}}. Cadw SAM: GM546: Cynon Corn-Drying Kiln</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Leat & Dam at Llanmihangel Mill\n|[[Leat]]\n|[[Margam]], (also [[Cornelly]]), <small>(see also [[List of Scheduled Monuments in Bridgend|Bridgend]])</small>\n|<small>{{coord|51.5282|-3.7012|name=Leat & Dam at Llanmihangel Mill|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS820824</small>\n|A three-storey watermill, with pit wheel, machinery and stones largely intact, having ceased use in 1940. The dam and leat bring water from the nearby [[River Cynfig]]. The site was recorded as a mill in 1291, but the remains are from the early 19th century.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(19th century)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM449</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|24944}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02876w}}. Cadw SAM: GM449: Leat & Dam at Llanmihangel Mill</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Remains of Blast Furnaces at Banwen\n|Blast Furnace\n|[[Onllwyn]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7811|-3.6425|name=Remains of Blast Furnaces at Banwen|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN867104</small>\n|The most intact of the [[ironworks]] on the [[anthracite]] coalfield. Built in 1845, and connected to the Swansea Canal by an [[edge rail]] wagonway, it may have produced no more than 80 tons of [[pig iron]]. Blast furnaces, charging platform, weighbridge and enginehouse all remain after its short-lived operation.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM420</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34071}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01566w}}. Cadw SAM: GM420: Remains of Blast Furnaces at Banwen</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Cwm Pelenna Colliery Ventilation Furnace\n|Industrial monument\n|[[Pelenna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6612|-3.7119|name=Cwm Pelenna Colliery Ventilation Furnace|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS816972</small>\n|Stone chimney and hillside flue, used to ventilate the coal mine in the 1830s. It was re-used in the mid-20th century, with a fan system.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM458</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|93276}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02884w}}. Cadw SAM: GM458: Cwm Pelenna Colliery Ventilation Furnace</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Bridge at Pontrhydyfen - geograph.org.uk - 65973.jpg|80px|Aqueduct (now cycleway) over the valley at Pontrhydyfen]]\n|[[Pontrhydyfen]] Aqueduct / Viaduct\n|[[Aqueduct (bridge)|Aqueduct]]\n|[[Pelenna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.633|-3.7415|name=Pontrhydyfen Aqueduct / Viaduct|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS795941</small>\n|Completed in 1825 to provide a [[wagonway]] across the Afan valley, it is a {{convert|425|yard|m}} bridge with four huge arches, and is also known as 'Y Bont Fawr' (The Big Bridge). It had a substantial trough to carry water across the valley to power the waterwheels of Cwmafon steelworks. It is now a cycle and pedestrian routeway. (A second viaduct crosses the river Afan to the west, taking a railway up Cwm Pelenna.)\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1825)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM393</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34857}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01015w}}. Cadw SAM: GM393: Pontrhydyfen Aqueduct / Viaduct</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Melin Court Blast Furnace\n|[[Blast Furnace]]\n|[[Resolven]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7027|-3.7022|name=Blast Furnace at Melin Court|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN824018</small>\n|Operating between 1708 and 1808 this is an early and significant ironworks, standing on precipitous cliffs above the Melincourt brook. Also known as Melincwrt Ironworks, it had furnace, foundry and a wide range of ancillary buildings, now standing in ruins among woodland.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1708)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM416</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34099}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01086w}}. Cadw SAM: GM416: Remains of Blast Furnace at Melin Court</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{CSS image crop|Image = Claypon's Tramroad Extension - geograph.org.uk - 1411584.jpg|bSize = 80|cWidth = 80| cHeight = 70| oTop = 10|oLeft = 0}}\n|Claypon's Tramroad at Ystradgynlais\n|[[Tramroad]]\n|[[Seven Sisters, Neath Port Talbot|Seven Sisters]], <small>(also [[Ystradgynlais]] and [[Tawe-Uchaf]], see [[List of Scheduled Monuments in Powys|Powys]])</small>\n|<small>{{coord|51.7734|-3.7218|name=Tramroad at Ystradgynlais|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN812097</small>\n|Early tramroad, bringing coal from Drim Colliery and limestone (needed as a [[Flux (metallurgy)|flux]]) from the quarries of [[Mynydd y Drum]] to the Ynyscedwyn Ironworks in the Swansea Valley. Built by Joseph Claypon in 1832 and in use until 1867, the tramroad linked with the [[Brecon Forest Tramroad]],<ref>[http://www.fforestfawrgeopark.org.uk/understanding/archaeology-industrial-heritage/the-brecon-forest-tramroad Fforest Fawr Geopark: The Brecon Forest Tramroad] accessed 3 March 2013</ref> and parts were later incorporated into the [[Swansea Vale Railway]].\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1832)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM399</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|80115}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00716w}}. Cadw SAM: GM399: Tramroad at Ystradgynlais</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:The remains of 'Parson's Folly Tramroad' - geograph.org.uk - 227920.jpg|80px|The remains of 'Parson's Folly' Tramroad]]\n|Parsons' Folly (Glyncorrwg Mineral Railway)\n|Railway\n|[[Tonna, Neath|Tonna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6691|-3.7514|name=Glyncorrwg Mineral Railway (Parsons Folly)|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS789981</small>\n|12&nbsp;km wagonway, with steep inclines to haul coal trucks over the hills from the Blaencregan colliery to the canals of the Neath valley. The construction and operating costs proved unfeasable and both Mr Parsons and his successor were bankrupted by the enterprise. Built between 1839 and 1842 with massive inclines and a steam-powered winding house, it was abandoned in 1852. The scheduled section is on the west side of Cefn Morfudd.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM447</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34840}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02878.0w}}. Cadw SAM: GM447: Glyncorrwg Mineral Railway (Parsons Folly) Section on Cefn Morfudd</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Remains of Lock and Dry Dock at Pantyffynnon\n|[[Lock (water transport)|Lock]]\n|[[Ystalyfera]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7513|-3.8003|name=Remains of Lock and Dry Dock at Pantyffynnon|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN758073</small>\n|At Lock 17 (or 'sawmill lock') of the [[Swansea Canal]], a dry dock was installed in 1875\u20136, shortly after the canal was sold to the [[Great Western Railway]]. The dry dock was alongside the normal lock, and enabled boats to be floated into place and rested on timber supports, so that the hull could be worked on after the water was emptied. Close by was the quay for Crimea Colliery (GM453)\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1875)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM397</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34491}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01046.36w}}. Cadw SAM: GM397: Remains of Lock and Dry Dock at Pantyffynnon</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{CSS image crop|Image=Engine House Tower - geograph.org.uk - 198276.jpg|bSize = 80|cWidth = 80|cHeight = 60| oTop = 50|oLeft = 0}}\n|[[Briton Ferry]] Dock Entrance\n|[[Dockyard]]\n|[[Briton Ferry]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.627|-3.8269|name=Briton Ferry Dock Entrance|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS736936</small>\n|Designed by Brunel in 1861, this had an experimental [[caisson (lock gate)|buoyant lockgate system]] between the tidal and inner docks in the Neath Estuary. \n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.8</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1861)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM445</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34238}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01972w}}. Cadw SAM: GM445: Briton Ferry Dock Entrance</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Cae'r Mynydd Ventilation Furnace and Mine\n|[[Colliery]]\n|[[Bryn, Neath Port Talbot|Bryn]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6204|-3.6944|name=Cae'r Mynydd Ventilation Furnace and Mine|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS827926</small>\n|Dated to early 19th century, before the development of powered fans for ventilation. A brazier within the furnace building created an updraft which sucked old air out of the mine, to be replaced by fresh air via other entrances. This furnace ventilated a [[drift mine]]. It is a well-preserved example of early mine ventilation technology.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.8</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM547</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|275896}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|04017w}}. Cadw SAM: GM547: Cae'r Mynydd Ventilation Furnace and Mine</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Pont Gam skew bridge at Aberdulais canal basin - geograph.org.uk - 1308356.jpg|80px|Skew bridge at Aberdulais canal basin]]\n|Canal Boat at [[Neath and Tennant Canal|Aberdulais Basin]]\n|[[Narrowboat|Canal Boat]]\n|[[Tonna, Neath|Tonna]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6794|-3.7752|name=Canal Boat at Aberdulais Basin|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS773993</small>\n|Aberdulais basin is the point where the [[Neath and Tennant canal]]s meet. Several old canal boats were abandoned beside the canal basin, and have now all but disappeared into the banks. The location of one, on the west bank of the Tennant canal, is a scheduled site.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.8</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM505</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|34531}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01070.18w}}. Cadw SAM: GM505: Canal Boat at Aberdulais Basin</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Swansea Canal Aqueduct at Ystalyfera - geograph.org.uk - 45095.jpg|80px|Swansea Canal Aqueduct at Ystalyfera]] \n|River Twrch Aqueduct, Ystalyfera\n|[[Navigable aqueduct|Aqueduct]]\n|[[Ystalyfera]], (also [[Ystradgynlais]]), <small>(see also [[List of Scheduled Monuments in Powys|Powys]])</small>\n|<small>{{coord|51.7684|-3.7799|name=Canal Aqueduct over the River Twrch, Ystalyfera|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN772092</small>\n|Stone aqueduct built over a weir, carrying the [[Swansea Canal]] over the River Twrch. Its three massive arches make it the largest of the five aqueducts on the canal. Built in 1798 by Thomas Sheasby, it was innovative in using [[Hydraulic cement]] to line the trough instead of puddled clay. Its proximity to the Capitol Cinema gave it the local name of 'Capitol Bridge'. It was restored in 1995 but is not currently water-filled, the canal route on either side being dry.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.8</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1798)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM396</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|109}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|01046.40w}}. Cadw SAM: GM396: Canal Aqueduct over the River Twrch, Ystalyfera</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Crimea Colliery & Canal Quay\n|[[Coal mine]]\n|[[Ystalyfera]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.7504|-3.8019|name=Crimea Colliery & Canal Quay|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN757072</small>\n|The Crimea coalmine only operated for 8 years, from 1854 to 1862, and the site has been abandoned ever since. Amongst the regenerating woodland are the substantial ruins of a beam-engine pumping-house, a winding house and chimney, and a complete surface layout of a mid-19th-century colliery. A short tramroad led to a quay on the [[Swansea Canal]], 200m south of the dry dock (GM397).\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.8</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1854)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM453</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|94711}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02889w}}. Cadw SAM: GM453: Crimea Colliery & Canal Quay</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Cilybebyll Auxiliary Unit Operational Base\n|Observation Post\n|[[Cilybebyll]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.723|-3.8101|name=Cilybebyll Auxiliary Unit Operational Base|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN750042</small>\n|Underground chamber in woodland, with a concrete floor, brick walls and corrugated iron roof. Built to be a concealed base for defense in the event of invasion.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.9</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1940s)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM620</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|413228}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|05773w}}. Cadw SAM: GM620: Cilybebyll Auxiliary Unit Operational Base</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Pentreclwydau Coalmine, Glynneath.JPG|80px|Pentreclwydau coalmine, Glynneath, a mid 20th century drift mine]]\n|Pentreclwydau Colliery\n|[[Coal mine]]\n|[[Glynneath]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.733|-3.669|name=Pentreclwydau Colliery|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SN848051</small>\n|Anthracite coalmine opened by the nationalised British Coal Board in 1957, and worked out 10 years later. It was a drift mine, driven sideways into the hillside south of Glynneath.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.9</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br>(1957)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM537</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|33523}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02186w}}. Cadw SAM: GM537: Pentreclwydau Colliery</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Coast Defence Radar Station - geograph.org.uk - 715191.jpg|80px|Coast Defence Radar Station overlooking Swansea Bay]]\n|[[Chain Home Low]] Radar Station, Margam\n|[[Radar station]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5698|-3.7428|name=Chain Home Low Radar Station, Margam|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS793871</small>\n|One of a network of early warning radar stations around the coast of Britain, constructed from 1941 to look for German bombers and shipping during [[World War II]]. They complemented the earlier [[Chain Home]] stations by being able to detect low-flying planes. The Margam station has three flat-topped buildings within the [[Margam Country Park|Country Park]], high on the escarpment, overlooking Port Talbot and Swansea Bay.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5.9</span>[[File:red pog.svg|10px]] Post-Medieval/ Modern<br> (1940s)\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM488</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|308125}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|02995w}}. Cadw SAM: GM488: Chain Home Low Radar Station, Margam</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{{GeoGroup}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Cadw properties]]\n*[[List of castles in Wales]]\n*[[List of hill forts in Wales]]\n*[[Historic houses in Wales]]\n*[[List of monastic houses in Wales]]\n*[[List of museums in Wales]]\n*[[List of Roman villas in Wales]]\n*[[Grade I listed buildings in Neath Port Talbot]]\n*[[Grade II* listed buildings in Neath Port Talbot]]\n\n==References==\n*<small>[[Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales#Coflein|Coflein]] is the online database of RCAHMW: [[Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Wales]], GGAT is the Glamorgan-Gwent Archaeological Trust, Cadw is the Welsh Historic Monuments Agency</small>\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Scheduled Monuments in Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of Scheduled Monuments in Wales|Neath Port Talbot]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Neath Port Talbot| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{location map+ |Wales Neath Port Talbot| AlternativeMap =Neath Port Talbot UK community map (blank).svg|float=right |width=250 |caption=Scheduled Monuments in Neath Port Talbot, Wales.<br> [[File:brown pog.svg|8px]]=Prehistoric  [[File:blue pog.svg|8px]]=Roman  [[File:green pog.svg|8px]]=Early Medieval <br>[[File:gold pog.svg|8px]]=Medieval  [[File:red pog.svg|8px]]=Post-Medieval/Modern|alt=Neath Port Talbot |places=\n{{