rrwg]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6327|-3.7064|name=Nant Herbert Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS819940</small>\n|Circular enclosure 22 m across, on sloping ground above the Nant Herbert Stream, within the Afan Argoed Forest Park. Although it was left as a clearing when the forest was planted, forestry work damaged much of the northern embankments.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM244</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307446}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00926w}}. Cadw SAM: GM244: Nant Herbert Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Ancient something - geograph.org.uk - 1035994.jpg|80px|Clearing in the trees at the ring cairn]]\n|Pebyll Ring Cairn\n|[[Ring cairn]]\n|[[Glyncorrwg]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.6634|-3.5764|name=Pebyll Ring Cairn|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS910972</small>\n|This is a large, oval stoney bank, some {{convert|30|m|ft}} across, with evidence of kerbstones on the inner and outer faces. A stone cist shows it was used for burials. It is sited on a ridge near the summit of Mynydd Blaengwynfi, close to the border with [[List of Scheduled Monuments in Rhondda Cynon Taf|Rhondda Cynon Taf]].\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.3</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[Bronze Age Britain|Bronze Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM330</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301297}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00721w}}. Cadw SAM: GM330: Pebyll Ring Cairn</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Tonmawr Camp\n|[[Enclosure (archaeology)|Enclosure]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5625|-3.6882|name=Camp 530m E of Tonmawr|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS830861</small>\n|Banked enclosure on a headland overlooking the upper reaches of the Afon Cynffig, to the east of Ton Mawr Farm. A bank and ditch enclose an oval 60\u201370 m across, with a less distinct outer enclosure linked to the inner ring, similar to the nearby Caer Cwmphilip (GM057), 1&nbsp;km to the NW.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM090</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301338}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00776w}}. Cadw SAM: GM090: Camp 530m E of Tonmawr. Scheduled area extended in 2002 to include outer enclosure</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Park, Caer Cwmphilip hillfort.JPG|80px|Concentric hillfort defenses at Caer Cwmphilip]]\n|Caer Cwmphilip\n|[[Enclosure (archaeology)|Enclosure]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5695|-3.6962|name=Camp N of Tonmawr|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS825870</small>\n|Concentric hillfort enclosure with a subrectanular inner defensive area 70m wide, surrounded by a much larger double banked series of defenses some 200 m across. It occupies a plateau west of Moel Ton Mawr summit, and south of the Nant Cwm Philip valley, with related Iron Age field systems to the east. It is known variously as Caer Cwmphilip and Moel Ton-Mawr.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM057</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301334}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00758w}}. Cadw SAM: GM057: Camp N of Tonmawr</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Park, Danish Camp.JPG|80px|Oval bank of Danish Camp, by Margam medieval deer park boundary.]]\n|Danish Camp\n|[[Enclosure (archaeology)|Enclosure]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5701|-3.7027|name=Danish Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS820870</small>\n|Oval bank 33\u00d742 m across. It is within a 20th-century forest plantation, although the area of the camp was left as a clearing. Margam medieval deer park boundary is nearby to the west, and Caer Cwmphilip (GM057) is 500m to the east, and both enclosures are on the same slope aboVe the Cwm Philip stream valley. It is also known as Cwm Philip West Enclosure.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM056</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307273}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00774w}}. Cadw SAM: GM056: Danish Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Ergyd Uchaf Round Barrow\n|Round cairn\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.586|-3.7246|name=Ergyd Uchaf Round Barrow|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS806888</small>\n|Round barrow in a small clearing in Margam Forest plantation. It is on a ridge 1.5&nbsp;km from the summit of Mynydd Margam. There is a substantial central hollow in the mound.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.3</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[Bronze Age Britain|Bronze Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM159</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|307288}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00749w}}. Cadw SAM: GM159: Ergyd Uchaf Round Barrow</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|<!--insert image here-->\n|Half Moon Camp\n|[[Enclosure (archaeology)|Enclosure]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5666|-3.7332|name=Half Moon Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS799867</small>\n|Small Hillfort on a hilltop north of Margam Abbey, on the opposite side of the valley from Mynydd y Castell (GM162). It is crossed by an upland section of the [[Wales Coast Path]].\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM477</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301319}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00745w}}. Cadw SAM: GM477: Half Moon Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Park - Mynydd y Castell Hillfort.JPG|80px|Mynydd y Castell Hillfort, in Margam Country Park]]\n|Mynydd y Castell Camp\n|Hillfort\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5653|-3.7237|name=Mynydd y Castell Camp|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS806865</small>\n|Large hillfort enclosing {{convert|2.7|ha|acres}} in a D shape, on an isolated hill 500m east of Margam Abbey. There has been some quarrying, and possible other uses, which may have disrupted layouts of banks and entrances. The hill is the start/finish of three long-distance paths: Ogwr Ridgeway Walk, Coed Morgannwg Way and [[St Illtyd's Walk]].\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM162</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301336}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00756w}}. Cadw SAM: GM162: Mynydd y Castell Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Park, Caer Blaen y Cwm enclosure.JPG|80px|Pre-Roman double bank, quadrangular enclosure on Mynydd Margam.]]\n|Caer Blaen-y-Cwm\n|[[Enclosure (archaeology)|Enclosure]]\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.579|-3.6851|name=Caer Blaen-y-Cwm|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS833880</small>\n|Double bank, defining a quadrangular enclosure 25 m across, on a broad ridge SE of Mynydd Margam, near the source of the [[River Kenfig]]. The enclosure was studied by [[Cyril Fox]] in 1934, who suggested it was a Roman Camp, and that nearby earthworks could be an outer defense, similar to that at Caer Cwmphilip (GM057), 1.5&nbsp;km to the SW. However it is now identified as pre-Roman, and the nearby earthworks to be later.\n|<span style=\"display:none\">1.5</span>[[File:brown pog.svg|10px]] Prehistoric<br>([[British Iron Age|Iron Age]])\n|style=\"vertical-align:top;\" |<small>GM058</small><br><ref>{{Watprn|coflein|301304}}. {{Watprn|GGAT|00759w}}. Cadw SAM: GM058: Roman Camp</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|[[File:Margam Park, Bodvoc stone - replica, in ring cairn.JPG|80px| Concrete replica of the Bodvoc Stone in the middle of the cairn]]\n|Site of [[Margam Stones Museum#No. 3. Bodvoc Stone|Bodvoc Stone]]\n|Ring cairn\n|[[Margam]]\n|<small>{{coord|51.5858|-3.6891|name=Site of Bodvoc Stone|region:GB_type:landmark}}, <br>SS830887</small>\n|Site of a 6th-century AD pillar inscribed 'The stone of Bodvoc', set in a Bronze Age cairn on the ridge near Mynydd Margam Summit. The original stone is now in [[Margam Stones 